The paper proposes a new technique for conflict analysis in Boolean CNF formulae that exploits learning to eliminate literals from the original clauses. This suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) or machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper involves the use of resolution and implication graphs, which are common techniques in the sub-categories of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper deals with simplification techniques, which could also place it in the sub-category of programming languages (cs.PL).
